The key insight is that the determinant is a multiplicative function, and for a linear map on a finite-dimensional space, the determinant is the product of the eigenvalues. The product formula for determinants states that the determinant of a linear map is the product of its determinants on the various p-adic and infinite places.

In the problem, the determinant of φ is calculated in the adeles. The determinant is a function from the group of invertible linear maps to the multiplicative group of the field. In our case, the field is the adele ring.

The determinant of φ in the adeles is given by the product of the determinant of φ in the p-adic places and the determinant of φ in the infinite place (related to the real determinant).

